00:23:30,556 --> 00:23:33,753
Said he was taking a year off work,
hitching around the world.

230
00:23:33,859 --> 00:23:37,386
<i>He was supposed to fly out a few weeks ago.</i>
<i>His ride never came.</i>

231
00:23:37,496 --> 00:23:40,431
He's been stuck with us ever since.

232
00:23:52,377 --> 00:23:54,277
Not bad.

233
00:23:57,015 --> 00:23:59,449
- That's the last one.
- All right.

234
00:23:59,551 --> 00:24:01,781
Well, we got a decent amount of water.

235
00:24:01,887 --> 00:24:04,355
We each drink a pint a day...

236
00:24:04,456 --> 00:24:08,187
that gives us enough for about 30 days,
if we don't exert ourselves.

237
00:24:08,293 --> 00:24:11,387
Which I'm guessin' wasn't a concern
with the rest of this crew.

238
00:24:11,497 --> 00:24:14,466
I don't see you breaking a sweat, stud.

239
00:24:16,568 --> 00:24:18,661
- Hey, che<i>f</i>.
- <i>Yo.</i>

240
00:24:18,771 --> 00:24:21,137
Chef, how are we doin' on food?

241
00:24:21,240 --> 00:24:25,040
Well, the good news is that
besides the powdered eggs...

242
00:24:25,144 --> 00:24:28,272
all the food's been canned
in water or juice.

243
00:24:28,380 --> 00:24:32,783
The bad news is, it's all peaches
and hearts of palm.

244
00:24:35,120 --> 00:24:37,588
Well, that buys us
a couple extra days.

245
00:24:37,689 --> 00:24:39,714
Ain't that just great news.

246
00:24:52,938 --> 00:24:54,906
So how screwed are we?

247
00:24:56,708 --> 00:24:58,972
[ Sighs ]
Pretty screwed.

248
00:24:59,077 --> 00:25:01,102
<i>[ AJ.]</i>
<i>Where are we?</i>

249
00:25:01,213 --> 00:25:05,172
Somewhere around here, in the middle of
the Yol Valley, 200 miles west of our course.

250
00:25:06,485 --> 00:25:09,648
- We're still in Mongolia?
- Nah.

251
00:25:09,755 --> 00:25:11,689
I think we're in China.

252
00:25:11,790 --> 00:25:14,122
J<i>ust over the border.</i>

253
00:25:14,226 --> 00:25:18,219
Wouldn't suppose there'd be
a Four Seasons Hotel out here, would there?

254
00:25:20,899 --> 00:25:25,165
Langhu, a few hundred miles
just due south of here.

255
00:25:25,270 --> 00:25:27,704
Well out of walking range.

256
00:25:30,509 --> 00:25:34,411
<i>/ could make it.</i>
<i>/ could walk to Langhu.</i>

257
00:25:34,513 --> 00:25:37,004
<i>/'m in good shape.</i>
<i>/ ran three marathons.</i>

258
00:25:37,149 --> 00:25:39,617
<i>[ Frank ]</i>
<i>/n a row, / hope.</i>

259
00:25:41,053 --> 00:25:43,453
Have you walked in the desert before?

260
00:25:44,656 --> 00:25:46,886
I hiked in the Mojave with my girlfriend.

261
00:25:46,992 --> 00:25:49,517
- [ Chuckles ]
- <i>This isn't the Mojave.</i>

262
00:25:49,628 --> 00:25:54,463
This is the Gobi. And let me warn you,
July is the hottest month in the Gobi.

263
00:25:54,566 --> 00:25:58,696
You will be taking a pint of water,
and you'll sweat 1 0.

264
00:26:02,341 --> 00:26:04,866
I'll just go by night.

265
00:26:04,977 --> 00:26:08,413
<i>You'd have to.</i>
<i>But how would you keep your course?</i>

266
00:26:08,513 --> 00:26:10,344
A compass.

267
00:26:10,482 --> 00:26:15,419
<i>Beyond these dunes,</i>
<i>we are surrounded by Altai Mountains.</i>

268
00:26:15,520 --> 00:26:17,750
<i>And they are mostly magnetic rock.</i>

269
00:26:19,725 --> 00:26:22,125
Have you ever seen a compass dance?

270
00:26:26,732 --> 00:26:29,599
What about this map?
I'll just take this map.

271
00:26:29,701 --> 00:26:32,135
How old is that map, Captain?

272
00:26:32,237 --> 00:26:35,536
Too old, the way the sand shifts
around here all the time.

273
00:26:35,641 --> 00:26:39,600
And Captain Towns's calculations
could be off by 20 percent.

274
00:26:39,711 --> 00:26:43,477
- No offense. I'm not saying that they are.
- None taken.

275
00:26:43,615 --> 00:26:46,584
But even if the captain
is one percent in error...

276
00:26:46,685 --> 00:26:49,279
<i>and you march 300 miles by the stars...</i>

277
00:26:49,421 --> 00:26:53,016
you'd miss Langhu, and you wouldn't
even know it was there to miss.

278
00:26:53,125 --> 00:26:55,025
You'd be walking in a circle.

279
00:26:55,127 --> 00:26:57,186
- <i>You're right-handed?</i>
- <i>Right.</i>

280
00:26:57,296 --> 00:27:01,596
<i>That means your right leg's more developed</i>
<i>than your left. You take a longer step with it.</i>

281
00:27:01,700 --> 00:27:04,066
You'd be walking
in a left-handed circle.

282
00:27:04,169 --> 00:27:06,729
You know what?
Forget it, all right? Y'all win, okay?

283
00:27:06,838 --> 00:27:09,568
<i>This isn't about winning or losing.</i>

284
00:27:09,675 --> 00:27:12,143
This is about staying alive.

285
00:27:19,017 --> 00:27:21,542
<i>[ Thunder Rumbling ]</i>

286
00:27:28,360 --> 00:27:30,260
Hey, Rod?

287
00:27:30,362 --> 00:27:32,125
Hmm?

288
00:27:33,465 --> 00:27:36,764
[ Nervous Chuckle ]
You don't--

289
00:27:36,868 --> 00:27:39,496
[ Whispering ]
You don't think the suit was right...

290
00:27:39,604 --> 00:27:41,799
do you?

291
00:27:41,907 --> 00:27:44,000
That I jinxed us or--

292
00:27:45,310 --> 00:27:47,778
Don't worry about it,John.

293
00:27:50,082 --> 00:27:52,573
Just try and get some sleep.

294
00:28:36,995 --> 00:28:40,328
[ Sighs, Chuckles ]
Maybe I should save this.

295
00:28:41,633 --> 00:28:43,601
<i>[ Zipper Zipping ]</i>

296
00:28:45,704 --> 00:28:49,231
[ Grunts, Gasping ]

297
00:28:52,611 --> 00:28:54,545
[ Screams ]
God!

298
00:28:56,982 --> 00:28:58,950
Oh, man.

299
00:29:02,954 --> 00:29:04,854
Hello?

300
00:29:17,235 --> 00:29:19,260
Help me!

301
00:29:47,899 --> 00:29:51,198
Kelly. You seen Davis this morning?

302
00:29:51,303 --> 00:29:54,238
Knowing him, he's still sleeping.

303
00:29:54,339 --> 00:29:56,398
- <i>[ Sammi ] Go wake his ass up.</i>
- Davis!

304
00:29:56,508 --> 00:29:58,976
Get up, you big baby!

305
00:30:00,679 --> 00:30:03,341
Davis!

306
00:30:03,482 --> 00:30:06,110
- Wake your ass up, man.
- Davis?

307
00:30:10,322 --> 00:30:13,450
[ Rodney ]
Well?

308
00:30:13,558 --> 00:30:15,355
His stuff s all here.

309
00:30:15,460 --> 00:30:17,860
<i>Any of you lads seen Davis this morning?</i>

310
00:30:17,963 --> 00:30:19,726
He's not there.

311
00:30:23,068 --> 00:30:24,968
<i>[ Kelly ]</i>

312
00:30:25,070 --> 00:30:27,368
- This was you...
- Davis?

313
00:30:27,472 --> 00:30:29,940
- telling him he jinxed us.
- Davis!

314
00:30:30,041 --> 00:30:32,339
- Oh, come on. I didn't mean that.
- Quit screwing around!

315
00:30:32,444 --> 00:30:34,412
- He couldn't have gone far.

316
00:30:34,513 --> 00:30:37,505
- Could he? Could he?

317
00:30:37,616 --> 00:30:41,712
- How the hell could we lose someone? Davis!
-John!

318
00:30:41,853 --> 00:30:44,583
We should have paired up.
Someone should have been watching him.

319
00:30:44,689 --> 00:30:46,657
Hey! Not another word from you.
You hear me?

320
00:30:46,791 --> 00:30:50,386
-John!

321
00:30:56,501 --> 00:30:59,766
- It's coming.

322
00:31:01,173 --> 00:31:03,607
<i>[ Frank ]</i>

323
00:31:06,578 --> 00:31:09,706
He's got to be out here somewhere.
I've got to go find him!

324
00:31:09,814 --> 00:31:12,214
Too late, Rodney!

325
00:31:12,350 --> 00:31:14,318
Hey! Get back here!

326
00:31:14,419 --> 00:31:17,752
Right. I'm not losing another friend out here.
I have to go and find him!

327
00:31:17,856 --> 00:31:20,188
No! No one else dies, understand?

328
00:31:20,292 --> 00:31:22,260
He's only a kid, for Christ's sake!

329
00:31:22,360 --> 00:31:24,954
- Alex! Alex!
- God!Jesus!John!

330
00:31:25,063 --> 00:31:28,521
Alex! Towns is right! He's right!

331
00:31:28,633 --> 00:31:30,931
- You can't help him!
-John!

332
00:31:31,036 --> 00:31:34,028
- You can't.
-John!

333
00:32:06,538 --> 00:32:08,665
[ Motor Buzzing ]

334
00:32:12,244 --> 00:32:16,544
What kind of odds do you give us
a search party's gonna find us?

335
00:32:17,682 --> 00:32:19,741
About five percent.

336
00:32:19,884 --> 00:32:21,852
Right. Five percent.

337
00:32:21,953 --> 00:32:24,251
So, based on a five-percent chance...

338
00:32:24,356 --> 00:32:27,655
you're gonna choose
to sit on your ass and do nothing?

339
00:32:29,227 --> 00:32:31,127
As opposed to what?

340
00:32:31,229 --> 00:32:34,096
Trying to figure a way out of here.

341
00:32:34,199 --> 00:32:37,965
- Look, we are in the middle of a desert...
- Yes. I know.

342
00:32:38,069 --> 00:32:40,833
with no radio, very little water,
even less food.

343
00:32:40,939 --> 00:32:43,931
If we try to walk out of here,
we're gonna last about two days.

344
00:32:44,042 --> 00:32:47,307
<i>The odds of crashing an airplane</i>

345
00:32:47,412 --> 00:32:49,539
so I would consider mysel<i>f</i>
an optimist.

346
00:32:49,648 --> 00:32:51,980
Or maybe just an asshole.

347
00:33:01,092 --> 00:33:03,993
All right.

348
00:33:04,095 --> 00:33:09,362
Listen, since Davis just disappeared,
they're pretty freaked out.

349
00:33:09,467 --> 00:33:12,095
- They should be.
- They're looking to you.

350
00:33:12,203 --> 00:33:14,330
Lady, this is not the Girl Scouts.

351
00:33:14,439 --> 00:33:18,273
I am not everybody's den mother.
They are grown men. They can deal with it.

352
00:33:18,376 --> 00:33:20,810
Thanks a lot.

353
00:33:22,013 --> 00:33:23,981
You're welcome.

354
00:33:35,093 --> 00:33:38,062
<i>Kelly, please, come sit with me.</i>

355
00:33:39,698 --> 00:33:41,666
I'm just curious.

356
00:33:41,766 --> 00:33:45,224
The pipe jacket in the back--
what's it all worth?

357
00:33:45,337 --> 00:33:48,670
Not much.
It's worn or used up. Nothing.

358
00:33:48,773 --> 00:33:50,900
It's the same with the tools.

359
00:33:51,009 --> 00:33:52,704
<i>Why?</i>

360
00:33:54,145 --> 00:33:57,114
Hang on a minute.

361
00:33:57,215 --> 00:33:59,706
You don't think anybody's coming.

362
00:33:59,818 --> 00:34:01,809
<i>Do you?</i>

363
00:34:01,953 --> 00:34:05,980
- Well, do you?
- I don't know, Alex.

364
00:34:08,093 --> 00:34:09,924
Don't be pathetic.

365
00:34:10,028 --> 00:34:13,054
<i>/'m telling you, they're coming.</i>

366
00:34:13,164 --> 00:34:15,223
I know they are.

367
00:34:15,333 --> 00:34:18,564
- <i>For who,you?</i>
- <i>Yes, for me.</i>

368
00:34:18,670 --> 00:34:20,570
And for you.

369
00:34:20,672 --> 00:34:23,300
They have a corporate responsibility
for all of us.

370
00:34:23,408 --> 00:34:27,344
They're out there right now, searching.
It's just a matter of time.

371
00:34:27,445 --> 00:34:31,905
<i>recommending our site be closed down, right?</i>

372
00:34:32,016 --> 00:34:34,576
Yes, I did.

373
00:34:34,719 --> 00:34:39,213
Don't you think they'd do the same thing
before mounting a search for us?

374
00:34:39,357 --> 00:34:41,257
Add it up.

375
00:34:43,428 --> 00:34:46,090
<i>[ Sammi ]</i>
<i>Don't kid yourself,/an.</i>

376
00:34:46,197 --> 00:34:49,098
We hitched a ride with the trash...

377
00:34:49,200 --> 00:34:51,634
not the other way around.

378
00:34:57,942 --> 00:35:01,673
[ Sighs ]

379
00:35:01,780 --> 00:35:05,443
Screw this. I'm outta here.

380
00:35:05,583 --> 00:35:08,552
Yeah, I'm coming with you,
and I'm taking some water.

381
00:35:08,653 --> 00:35:10,780
No one touches the water!

382
00:35:10,922 --> 00:35:14,619
Hey. Whoa. What's going on here?

383
00:35:14,726 --> 00:35:16,660
- What does it look like?
- Hey!

384
00:35:16,761 --> 00:35:18,729
- Get back here!
- Hey!

385
00:35:20,432 --> 00:35:23,629
- [ All Shouting ]
-<i>[ Frank ] Hey, knock it off.</i>

386
00:35:23,735 --> 00:35:26,135
- Go back!
- Let go!

387
00:35:28,506 --> 00:35:30,997
[ Agitated Shouting, Indistinct ]

388
00:35:31,109 --> 00:35:33,236
It's gone, you fools!

389
00:35:34,746 --> 00:35:37,806
- [ Whistles ]
-<i>[ Shouting Continues ]</i>

390
00:35:37,949 --> 00:35:39,917
I have an idea.

391
00:35:40,051 --> 00:35:41,951
I have an idea.

392
00:35:42,053 --> 00:35:44,021
I can get us out of here.

393
00:35:44,122 --> 00:35:46,522
I can get us out of here.

394
00:35:48,526 --> 00:35:51,791
I've been examining the plane.

395
00:35:51,896 --> 00:35:54,729
You see, the-- the C-1 1 9...

396
00:35:54,833 --> 00:35:57,859
is a twin-boom design...

397
00:35:57,969 --> 00:36:01,302
and the starboard boom here
isn't damaged...

398
00:36:01,406 --> 00:36:04,637
which is great because if-if
the starboard engine stays where it is--

399
00:36:04,742 --> 00:36:07,540
at the forward end
of the starboard boom--

400
00:36:07,645 --> 00:36:11,206
this boom then becomes the fuselage...

401
00:36:11,349 --> 00:36:13,317
becomes the plane.

402
00:36:13,418 --> 00:36:15,477
<i>Do you see what /'m saying?</i>

403
00:36:15,620 --> 00:36:20,887
<i>And-And while the port area</i>
<i>of the tail unit is intact...</i>

404
00:36:20,992 --> 00:36:24,689
we will still have to redesign
the tail section.

405
00:36:24,796 --> 00:36:26,957
What the hell is he talking about?

406
00:36:27,065 --> 00:36:29,556
He's talking about
building a new airplane.

407
00:36:29,667 --> 00:36:33,228
- Out of the old one.
-<i>[ Elliott ] Yes, Captain.</i>

408
00:36:33,338 --> 00:36:35,898
And flying ourselves out of here.

409
00:36:36,007 --> 00:36:38,999
Yeah, why didn't I think of that?

410
00:36:39,110 --> 00:36:42,011
<i>Why don't we build a swimming pool,</i>
<i>while we're at it?</i>

411
00:36:42,113 --> 00:36:44,240
[ Laughing ]
Oh, that's funny.

412
00:36:44,382 --> 00:36:46,282
<i>Yeah.</i>

413
00:36:47,552 --> 00:36:50,350
Well, you know,
there are no component problems...

414
00:36:50,455 --> 00:36:52,923
<i>and we have all the parts and tools</i>
<i>we need on board.</i>

415
00:36:53,024 --> 00:36:56,460
- I assure you, we can do it.
- It's impossible.

416
00:36:56,561 --> 00:36:59,689
At first glance, it seems impossible
that a bee should fly...

417
00:36:59,797 --> 00:37:01,628
but it does.

418
00:37:01,733 --> 00:37:04,566
I think a bee stung you
on your big dumb-ass head.

419
00:37:06,571 --> 00:37:09,062
What do you know about airplanes?

420
00:37:09,173 --> 00:37:11,641
I design them, Mr. Towns.

421
00:37:11,743 --> 00:37:14,211
That's what I know about airplanes.

422
00:37:17,148 --> 00:37:21,414
<i>You might have mentioned that little piece</i>
<i>of information a bit earlier on, Elliott.</i>

423
00:37:25,390 --> 00:37:28,757
Who do you work for?
What company?

424
00:37:28,860 --> 00:37:31,920
Sizemore and Pratt.
They're in Long Beach.

425
00:37:32,030 --> 00:37:34,123
They do mostly experimental aircraft.

426
00:37:34,232 --> 00:37:39,192
Mm-hmm. And you understand that
engine's got a 2,000-pound thrust?

427
00:37:39,304 --> 00:37:43,638
- Yes. So?
- When it gets started,
it's gonna tear your bee apart.

428
00:37:43,741 --> 00:37:47,177
Well, you'll just have to
be careful this time.

429
00:37:47,278 --> 00:37:51,806
The design is perfect. The only flaw
is that we have to rely on you to fly it.

430
00:37:53,751 --> 00:37:55,651
[ Scoffs ]

431
00:37:57,689 --> 00:38:00,522
I say we build the damn plane.
Why the hell not?

432
00:38:00,625 --> 00:38:02,593
- Get us out of here.
- Let's build it, man.

433
00:38:02,694 --> 00:38:05,185
It's better than doin' nothin',
fightin' over water.

434
00:38:05,296 --> 00:38:09,232
- It's worth a try.
- Oh, yeah. It's worth a try!

435
00:38:09,334 --> 00:38:13,703
If we had a few months and an unlimited
supply of water, which we don't.

436
00:38:13,805 --> 00:38:16,706
<i>And if you do try,you won't live</i>

437
00:38:16,808 --> 00:38:19,436
None of you will.

438
00:38:19,544 --> 00:38:23,446
- We could work.
- So what do <i>you</i> think we should do?

439
00:38:24,849 --> 00:38:26,817
- Nothing.
- What?

440
00:38:26,918 --> 00:38:31,355
<i>The longer we wait, the better chance</i>
<i>we have of somebody spotting us.</i>

441
00:38:46,704 --> 00:38:49,002
Where's Liddle?

442
00:38:53,378 --> 00:38:55,278
Oh, shit.

443
00:38:55,380 --> 00:38:57,780
Has anybody seen Liddle?

444
00:38:57,915 --> 00:39:00,315
He's definitely not in here.

445
00:39:00,451 --> 00:39:02,919
Oh, God. We lost another one.

446
00:39:08,059 --> 00:39:10,254
He'll never make it.

447
00:39:10,361 --> 00:39:12,329
Shit.

448
00:39:16,501 --> 00:39:19,595
Maybe he doesn't give your sit-on-your-ass-
and-do-nothing plan much hope.

449
00:39:19,704 --> 00:39:22,832
Hey, you're not going after him.

450
00:39:22,940 --> 00:39:25,204
No one else dies, remember?

451
00:39:31,749 --> 00:39:33,717
I'll go.

452
00:39:34,786 --> 00:39:36,754
I'll bring him back.

453
00:39:38,423 --> 00:39:41,153
- A.J.?
- Yeah?

454
00:39:41,259 --> 00:39:43,454
Throw me that canteen.

455
00:39:46,831 --> 00:39:48,560
Good luck.

456
00:39:52,036 --> 00:39:56,666
- Yeah.
- Captain, Liddle's first name is James.

457
00:39:58,076 --> 00:39:59,976
Jimbo.

458
00:40:42,820 --> 00:40:45,288
Liddle!

459
00:41:05,943 --> 00:41:07,843
Liddle!

460
00:41:50,788 --> 00:41:53,086
No.

461
00:42:03,734 --> 00:42:06,032
<i>[ Flies Buzzing ]</i>

462
00:42:10,274 --> 00:42:13,971
[ Gagging ]

463
00:42:24,655 --> 00:42:26,919
<i>Someone's already been here.</i>

464
00:42:28,993 --> 00:42:30,961
The dead guy's Kyle.

465
00:42:31,062 --> 00:42:33,189
<i>He had a really nice Seiko.</i>

466
00:42:33,297 --> 00:42:37,529
<i>/ know, 'cause he won it from me</i>
<i>in a poker game back at the patch.</i>

467
00:42:41,138 --> 00:42:43,766
Someone came along and took it.

468
00:42:43,875 --> 00:42:45,775
Nomads.

469
00:42:45,877 --> 00:42:50,507
Smugglers, probably.
That's the last thing we need.

470
00:42:52,250 --> 00:42:54,150
You okay?

471
00:42:56,020 --> 00:42:57,988
I'm not going back.

472
00:42:59,056 --> 00:43:01,889
I'm just resting.

473
00:43:01,993 --> 00:43:04,928
You look like you could use some water.

474
00:43:16,974 --> 00:43:19,408
So,just between the two of us--

475
00:43:23,547 --> 00:43:26,277
<i>no bullshit, Captain Towns</i>--

476
00:43:26,417 --> 00:43:29,614
do you think they're ever gonna find us?

477
00:43:31,522 --> 00:43:33,615
It's a long shot.

478
00:43:36,861 --> 00:43:39,022
So why not try and build the plane?

479
00:43:39,130 --> 00:43:41,860
Why give people false hope?

480
00:43:41,966 --> 00:43:43,934
Come on, man.

481
00:43:45,303 --> 00:43:48,033
Most people spend
their whole lives hanging on...

482
00:43:48,139 --> 00:43:52,041
<i>to hopes and dreams that are never gonna</i>
<i>come true, but they hold on to 'em.</i>

483
00:43:52,143 --> 00:43:55,635
Why are you gonna give up on 'em now
when you need 'em most?

484
00:43:55,746 --> 00:44:00,615
You're assuming I'm one of those people
who has hopes and dreams.

485
00:44:02,486 --> 00:44:06,047
I find it hard to believe that a man
who learns to fly never had a dream.

486
00:44:10,127 --> 00:44:13,619
Look, how could I let those people
build that plane...

487
00:44:13,731 --> 00:44:16,131
when I don't believe it'll work?

488
00:44:16,233 --> 00:44:20,693
And every day they waste trying to build it
brings 'em one day closer to dying.

489
00:44:25,910 --> 00:44:29,038
I think a man only needs
one thing in life.

490
00:44:29,146 --> 00:44:32,138
He just needs someone to love.

491
00:44:32,249 --> 00:44:36,481
If you can't give him that,
then give him something to hope for.

492
00:44:36,587 --> 00:44:40,819
<i>And if you can't give him that...</i>

493
00:44:40,925 --> 00:44:43,860
just give him something to do.

494
00:44:56,941 --> 00:45:00,035
James, you'll never make it.

495
00:45:00,144 --> 00:45:02,044
[ Sighs ]

496
00:45:03,414 --> 00:45:06,042
Then I'll die trying.

497
00:45:08,552 --> 00:45:11,020
There are people counting on me.

498
00:45:16,227 --> 00:45:19,424
Okay! Okay, okay.

499
00:45:20,965 --> 00:45:22,865
Okay.

500
00:45:22,967 --> 00:45:25,458
We'll build it.

501
00:45:25,569 --> 00:45:27,537
Just come back with me.

502
00:45:30,274 --> 00:45:33,175
How do I know you're not full of shit?

503
00:45:33,277 --> 00:45:35,177
[ Sighs ]

504
00:45:43,421 --> 00:45:45,651
Here.

505
00:45:45,756 --> 00:45:47,656
Take it.

506
00:45:47,758 --> 00:45:51,751
You can give it back when we get home.

507
00:45:55,299 --> 00:45:56,323
[ Beeping ]

508
00:45:56,400 --> 00:45:57,458
[ Beeping ]

509
00:46:17,555 --> 00:46:20,524
- What?
- Nothing.

510
00:46:20,624 --> 00:46:23,252
- I'm just amazed.
- By what?

511
00:46:23,360 --> 00:46:25,328
That during these dire times...

512
00:46:25,429 --> 00:46:28,330
you take the time
to thank God for anything.

513
00:46:28,432 --> 00:46:31,959
Well, we're still alive, aren't we?

514
00:46:34,004 --> 00:46:36,768
Let me tell you a story.

515
00:46:36,874 --> 00:46:39,809
A rabbi and a priest
attend a boxing match.

516
00:46:39,910 --> 00:46:43,175
They watch as the boxers
come into the ring.

517
00:46:43,280 --> 00:46:47,512
The rabbi sees one of the boxers
cross himself.

518
00:46:47,651 --> 00:46:50,882
<i>So the rabbi turns to the priest</i>
<i>and asks...</i>

519
00:46:50,988 --> 00:46:53,786
''What does that mean?''

520
00:46:53,891 --> 00:46:58,851
The priest says, ''Not a damn thing
if the man can't fight.''

521
00:46:58,963 --> 00:47:00,897
[ Chuckles ]

522
00:47:09,673 --> 00:47:11,903
<i>[ Sammi ]</i>

523
00:47:27,958 --> 00:47:31,325
- There you go.
- Yeah.

524
00:47:31,428 --> 00:47:33,726
<i>[ Frank Sighs ]</i>

525
00:47:34,865 --> 00:47:37,299
[ Gruff Voice ]
Liddle and I had a talk.

526
00:47:38,736 --> 00:47:41,034
I think we should build the plane.

527
00:47:41,138 --> 00:47:42,969
Wha--

528
00:47:43,073 --> 00:47:45,234
<i>Elliott...</i>

529
00:47:45,342 --> 00:47:48,368
can you really design this thing
the way you said you could?

530
00:47:48,479 --> 00:47:51,642
- <i>No bullshit?</i>
- Yes, I can.

531
00:47:53,951 --> 00:47:57,580
Well, we're either all in this together
or no one at all.

532
00:47:57,721 --> 00:47:59,689
<i>No compromises.</i>

533
00:48:03,460 --> 00:48:05,360
I'm in.

534
00:48:05,462 --> 00:48:07,157
Yeah.

535
00:48:08,499 --> 00:48:10,399
Yeah, me too.

536
00:48:10,501 --> 00:48:12,867
Shit. Me three.

537
00:48:12,970 --> 00:48:14,562
Okay.

538
00:48:16,407 --> 00:48:18,375
Get some rest.

539
00:48:18,475 --> 00:48:21,069
We start tonight.

540
00:48:21,178 --> 00:48:23,806
[ Kelly ]
Let's take them inside. It's cooler.

541
00:48:23,914 --> 00:48:26,576
- Hold on.
- Let me take this.

542
00:48:31,021 --> 00:48:35,481
- [ Grunts ]
- If we do this, we'll be cutting our lives in half.

543
00:48:35,593 --> 00:48:38,061
We'll be drinking twice
as much water, Frank.

544
00:48:38,162 --> 00:48:40,687
We don't have any other choice.

545
00:48:40,798 --> 00:48:43,426
Why?

546
00:48:43,534 --> 00:48:46,196
'Cause it's too early to give up, A.J....

547
00:48:46,303 --> 00:48:48,771
and too late to do anything else.

548
00:48:48,872 --> 00:48:52,603
I'm glad that you've finally
seen the light, Mr. Towns.

549
00:48:58,515 --> 00:49:00,506
Hey.

550
00:49:00,651 --> 00:49:02,846
Let's get one thing straight.

551
00:49:02,987 --> 00:49:06,115
I'm not taking orders from you.

552
00:49:08,959 --> 00:49:11,257
Get some rest.

553
00:49:17,835 --> 00:49:19,803
Hey, Towns.

554
00:49:21,639 --> 00:49:23,903
Thanks.

555
00:49:24,008 --> 00:49:26,203
Are you kidding me?

556
00:49:26,310 --> 00:49:29,802
I'd do anything to avoid another
hopes-and-dreams speech.

557
00:49:37,955 --> 00:49:41,391
[ Elliott ] Okay, gentlemen, our-our
first task is to separate the wing here...

558
00:49:41,525 --> 00:49:45,484
so-- so we can join it
with the main fuselage, okay?

559
00:49:56,040 --> 00:49:58,440
<i>[ Sammi ]</i>

560
00:49:59,476 --> 00:50:02,445
[ Motor Humming ]

561
00:50:04,682 --> 00:50:06,946
I'm gonna need some help.

562
00:50:26,870 --> 00:50:30,738
- Make sure they're good and tight, Ian, eh?
- <i>All right.</i>

563
00:50:33,877 --> 00:50:35,777
There you go.

564
00:50:35,879 --> 00:50:38,746
You still got some of them
old muscles up there, don't you?

565
00:50:38,882 --> 00:50:43,114
<i>[ Elliott ] You guys need to be careful</i>
<i>when you step on the wing, okay?</i>

566
00:50:43,253 --> 00:50:46,689
<i>Man, / thought this would be easy.</i>

567
00:50:46,824 --> 00:50:48,724
Hey, no coffee breaks.

568
00:50:48,826 --> 00:50:51,260
That means you too.

569
00:50:51,362 --> 00:50:54,331
You know, I liked him a lot better
when all he did was hum.

570
00:50:54,431 --> 00:50:57,628
<i>[ AJ. Laughing ]</i>
<i>Yeah,you still got it.</i>

571
00:51:00,037 --> 00:51:02,301
Whoa! Aah!

572
00:51:04,875 --> 00:51:07,070
- Watch what you're doin', man.
- You got it, Rod?

573
00:51:07,177 --> 00:51:09,077
Hang on.

574
00:51:09,246 --> 00:51:11,612
- <i>[ Rodney ] On three,yeah?</i>
- <i>[Jeremy ] Let's do it.</i>

575
00:51:11,749 --> 00:51:14,377
[ Rodney ]
One, two, three!

576
00:51:18,255 --> 00:51:21,418
- There you go!

577
00:51:21,525 --> 00:51:26,087
- [ All Cheering ]
- Yeah, baby! Yeah!

578
00:51:26,196 --> 00:51:28,391
[ Whooping ]

579
00:51:32,469 --> 00:51:34,596
I'll be damned.

580
00:51:34,705 --> 00:51:37,173
<i>That's a start, Frank.</i>

581
00:51:45,482 --> 00:51:47,643
Oh, geez.
Somebody turn out the lights.

582
00:51:47,785 --> 00:51:52,222
- How much water did we drink?
- Too much.

583
00:51:52,322 --> 00:51:55,553
And that's at night.
[ Groans ]

584
00:51:59,696 --> 00:52:02,324
<i>[ Torch Crackling ]</i>

585
00:52:08,739 --> 00:52:10,570
Two-eighths.

586
00:52:13,110 --> 00:52:15,738
- Frank.
- Hmm?

587
00:52:15,846 --> 00:52:18,178
You okay?

588
00:52:18,315 --> 00:52:20,783
When I was out there,
when I found Liddle...

589
00:52:20,884 --> 00:52:24,479
- Yeah?
- I saw something pretty weird.

590
00:52:24,621 --> 00:52:27,249
What?

591
00:52:27,357 --> 00:52:30,622
You know that poor son of a bitch
that fell out of the airplane?

592
00:52:30,727 --> 00:52:35,494
- Yeah?
- I found shell casings all around his body.

593
00:52:35,599 --> 00:52:38,397
Looked like someone had been
using him for target practice.

594
00:52:38,502 --> 00:52:41,733
Oh... shit.

595
00:52:44,775 --> 00:52:47,710
Just keep that to yourself, all right?

596
00:52:47,811 --> 00:52:50,780
I don't want to give 'em
anything more to worry about.

597
00:52:50,881 --> 00:52:52,872
Here.

598
00:53:00,457 --> 00:53:02,948
- Oh, yeah.

599
00:53:03,060 --> 00:53:05,528
<i>Hey, Patch.</i>

600
00:53:05,629 --> 00:53:10,259
How 'bout a nice ice-cold
double mint Frappuccino?

601
00:53:10,367 --> 00:53:13,063
Screw that.
How 'bout a Bacardi and Coke?

602
00:53:13,170 --> 00:53:15,161
Ahh. With a lot of ice.

603
00:53:15,272 --> 00:53:18,799
- And one of'em little umbrella things.
- Yeah!

604
00:53:18,909 --> 00:53:21,742
- How 'bout a hamburger with a lot of cheese?
- Whoa, whoa.

605
00:53:21,845 --> 00:53:25,042
Hamburger, yeah. Cheese, mmm.
I'm tryin' to watch my figure, you know?

606
00:53:25,182 --> 00:53:27,150
[ Laughing ]
Yeah!

607
00:53:30,220 --> 00:53:33,712
- One day.
- <i>Yeah. Someday soon, man.</i>

608
00:53:33,857 --> 00:53:36,052
[ Chuckles ]

609
00:53:50,741 --> 00:53:52,709
How's it going?

610
00:53:55,379 --> 00:53:57,745
[ Gasping ]

611
00:54:04,454 --> 00:54:07,218
- Is everybody okay?
- Sammi!

612
00:54:07,324 --> 00:54:09,554
Ah, geez.

613
00:54:09,660 --> 00:54:12,857
<i>Oh, my God.</i>

614
00:54:12,963 --> 00:54:14,954
Everybody here?

615
00:54:15,065 --> 00:54:17,761
<i>Oh, Christ.</i>

616
00:54:17,868 --> 00:54:21,531
<i>Oh, no.</i>
<i>Tell me that wasn't all the fuel.</i>

617
00:54:36,553 --> 00:54:40,785
<i>We're gonna need</i>
<i>the remaining fuel for the plane.</i>

618
00:54:40,891 --> 00:54:44,691
- We're gonna have to work during the day.
- What?

619
00:54:44,795 --> 00:54:49,562
[ Scoffs ] And what kind of hole
is that gonna put us in with the H2O?

620
00:54:49,666 --> 00:54:53,158
We're gonna run out before
we even finish the damn plane.

621
00:54:55,005 --> 00:54:59,305
<i>[ /an ] Not necessarily. Day shift output</i>
<i>is always higher than night anyway.</i>

622
00:54:59,409 --> 00:55:02,776
If we add in the fact that we're gonna
be able to see what we're doing...

623
00:55:02,879 --> 00:55:05,746
I'd estimate
that our productivity per pint...

624
00:55:05,882 --> 00:55:07,782
would actually increase.

625
00:55:09,019 --> 00:55:11,817
We'd drink more, finish sooner.

626
00:55:20,030 --> 00:55:22,692
<i>[ Rodney ]</i>
<i>'Come to the Gobi, 'they said.</i>

627
00:55:22,799 --> 00:55:25,427
''Great prospects,'' they said.

628
00:55:25,535 --> 00:55:29,665
''Sun, sand, oil.''

629
00:55:29,773 --> 00:55:32,241
Well, two out of three ain't bad.

630
00:55:33,844 --> 00:55:36,039
<i>[ Motor Humming ]</i>

631
00:55:42,853 --> 00:55:45,219
How's it coming?

632
00:55:45,322 --> 00:55:47,449
- What?
- <i>How's it coming?</i>

633
00:55:47,557 --> 00:55:51,015
- Good.
- <i>Good. Well, don't take all day.</i>

634
00:55:53,630 --> 00:55:56,531
<i>And you two can step it up here as well.</i>

635
00:55:56,633 --> 00:55:58,601
<i>Get a move on.</i>

636
00:56:15,552 --> 00:56:19,044
- Okay. Go for it.
- All right. Here goes.

637
00:56:19,189 --> 00:56:23,182
Easy, Towns.
For God's sake, this is surgery!

638
00:56:26,530 --> 00:56:28,430
- Whoa!
- Whoa!

639
00:56:28,532 --> 00:56:30,432
<i>[ Cheering ]</i>

640
00:56:30,534 --> 00:56:32,832
- Yeah!
- Yeah!

641
00:56:32,936 --> 00:56:36,372
- Whoa! Yeah!
- Yeah!

642
00:56:36,473 --> 00:56:38,373
Yes!

643
00:56:38,475 --> 00:56:41,774
- Hey, give me some.
- <i>[ Frank ] How's it look, AJ.?</i>

644
00:56:41,878 --> 00:56:43,846
<i>[ AJ.]</i>

645
00:56:43,980 --> 00:56:46,346
So, gentlemen...

646
00:56:47,884 --> 00:56:49,784
and lady...

647
00:56:49,886 --> 00:56:53,549
our task today is to mate
the port wing with the starboard.

648
00:56:53,657 --> 00:56:55,557
Okay?

649
00:56:58,862 --> 00:57:01,729
For that, Sammi, we need you. Okay?

650
00:57:06,870 --> 00:57:09,395
You sure you know what to do?

651
00:57:09,506 --> 00:57:11,736
Yeah, I think so.

652
00:57:11,842 --> 00:57:14,834
<i>[ Elliott ]</i>
<i>Sammi,you have tojoin the wings.</i>

653
00:57:14,945 --> 00:57:18,176
We have only one chance with this.
If it doesn't work, we don't fly.

654
00:57:18,315 --> 00:57:21,113
And we all die horribly.

655
00:57:21,251 --> 00:57:23,242
Yeah, no pressure on me, right?

656
00:57:23,386 --> 00:57:27,584
Just a little bit.
But you'll be a'right, man.

657
00:57:27,691 --> 00:57:29,659
Make us proud.

658
00:57:34,064 --> 00:57:35,964
Whew.

659
00:57:36,066 --> 00:57:38,500
What am I doing? I'm a chef.

660
00:57:38,602 --> 00:57:40,502
[ Exhales ]

661
00:57:40,604 --> 00:57:42,504
<i>[ Frank ]</i>

662
00:57:44,608 --> 00:57:47,577
- [ All Chattering ]
-Jeremy, keep in line with Rodney.

663
00:57:52,215 --> 00:57:53,944
[ Creaking ]

664
00:57:54,084 --> 00:57:57,144
- Stayin' straight?
- <i>Yeah.</i>

665
00:57:58,755 --> 00:58:00,313
- <i>[ All Shouting ]</i>
-Jeremy!

666
00:58:00,423 --> 00:58:03,153
Don't let go! Don't let go!

667
00:58:03,260 --> 00:58:05,387
Watch out, Sammi!

668
00:58:05,495 --> 00:58:06,985
- I got it!

669
00:58:08,932 --> 00:58:11,127
- No!
- Get back!

670
00:58:11,234 --> 00:58:13,168
Shit!

671
00:58:16,773 --> 00:58:18,434
Oh, Sammi.

672
00:58:32,956 --> 00:58:35,652
See? Piece of cake.

673
00:58:35,759 --> 00:58:38,523
- [ All Laughing ]
- You mad Mexican bastard!

674
00:58:38,628 --> 00:58:40,653
What were you thinking?

675
00:58:40,764 --> 00:58:42,664
Sammi!

676
00:58:42,766 --> 00:58:44,666
Jesus!

677
00:58:44,768 --> 00:58:46,668
Anybody got a change of underwear?

678
00:58:46,770 --> 00:58:48,670
<i>[ Liddle ]</i>
<i>You can always borrow Rady's.</i>

679
00:58:48,772 --> 00:58:52,674
- <i>/'m not sure how clean they are though.</i>
- <i>You made us proud, Sammi.</i>

680
00:58:52,776 --> 00:58:54,744
<i>[ Rodney ]</i>
<i>Thought you'd shit yourself.</i>

681
00:58:56,346 --> 00:58:56,744
- Oh, yeah. That's what I'm talkin' about.

682
00:58:56,813 --> 00:58:59,145
- Oh, yeah. That's what I'm talkin' about.

683
00:59:00,483 --> 00:59:02,314
No, no. What are you doin'?

684
00:59:02,419 --> 00:59:05,013
- God, please. Turn this shit off.
- What's the problem?

685
00:59:05,155 --> 00:59:08,056
- Listen, man, your deejay rights
have been revoked.

686
00:59:15,799 --> 00:59:18,700
Hey, I was gonna play that next, man.

687
00:59:56,740 --> 00:59:59,106
[ Laughing ]

688
01:00:09,986 --> 01:00:11,419
Hey.

689
01:00:15,725 --> 01:00:17,022
Cheers, man.

690
01:00:20,931 --> 01:00:22,626
Them things'll kill ya.

691
01:00:22,732 --> 01:00:26,759
.'.'<i>[ Continues ]</i>

692
01:00:48,024 --> 01:00:51,516
.'.'<i>[ Ends ]</i>

693
01:00:51,628 --> 01:00:53,528
- Hey, what are you doing, Ian?
- [ Beeping ]

694
01:00:53,630 --> 01:00:56,428
Oh,just sending an e-mail
to an old friend.

695
01:00:56,533 --> 01:00:58,967
What? Really?

696
01:01:02,038 --> 01:01:04,598
- <i>[ Beeping ]</i>
- You're a funny fucker.

697
01:01:07,043 --> 01:01:08,908
[ Laughing ]

698
01:01:09,012 --> 01:01:10,946
<i>[ Liquid Pouring ]</i>

699
01:01:12,082 --> 01:01:13,982
No, no, no, no.

700
01:01:14,084 --> 01:01:16,518
We do not have time
for rods and linkages.

701
01:01:16,619 --> 01:01:19,520
As you should know, we have
an extremely large lifting surface.

702
01:01:19,622 --> 01:01:21,522
It's oversized for the weight load.

703
01:01:21,624 --> 01:01:24,525
<i>We won't need more than</i>
<i>1 0 to 1 5 degrees of pitch control...</i>

704
01:01:24,627 --> 01:01:27,027
<i>and all of that will need to be</i>
<i>nose-down pitched.</i>

705
01:01:27,130 --> 01:01:29,360
<i>That's where we need to apply</i>
<i>better torque flexing.</i>

706
01:01:29,466 --> 01:01:31,866
<i>Are you even listening to me?</i>

707
01:01:31,968 --> 01:01:33,868
<i>[ Thunder Rumbling ]</i>

708
01:01:33,970 --> 01:01:36,734
Maybe it'll rain.

709
01:01:36,840 --> 01:01:39,308
<i>[ Rain Falling ]</i>

710
01:01:55,725 --> 01:01:58,421
It <i>is</i> raining.
[ Chuckles ]

711
01:02:00,463 --> 01:02:03,364
